{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b644b787-48fa-4aab-a907-2db72c688cc6","content":"The most likely issue is that **your JDK version is too old**. Current .NET MAUI Android builds (.NET 9+) require **JDK 21**, not JDK 17. The Android SDK build-tools and Gradle plugin versions shipped with recent .NET workloads dropped JDK 17 support.\n\n**Fix — install Temurin JDK 21 and update JAVA_HOME:**\n\n```bash\nbrew install --cask temurin@21\nexport JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 21)\n```\n\nThen make it permanent by adding to your `~/.zshrc`:\n\n```bash\necho 'export JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 21)' >> ~/.zshrc\n```\n\nAfter that, rebuild your project. If you want to confirm .NET picks up the right JDK, run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -bl\n```\n\nand inspect the binlog for the `JavaSdkDirectory` property — it should point to your JDK 21 installation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"99bd4548-2f8f-4490-bd2b-4061490ce2b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about what's likely going on here. .NET MAUI Android builds require a specific Java version. As of recent .NET versions:\n\n- .NET 8 / MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 / MAUI may require JDK 17 as well\n\nBut the common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is the **JAVA_HOME path**. \n\nOn macOS, the JDK installation structure is different than on Linux or Windows—the actual JDK files live inside a `Contents/Home` subdirectory within the `.jdk` bundle. So if Temurin 17 is installed at `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk`, the JAVA_HOME should point to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, not just the `.jdk` folder itself. This is a frequent source of build failures because the build tools can't find the Java compiler or libraries when the path is incorrect.\n\nThe real complication with .NET MAUI on Android is that starting with .NET 8, the Microsoft.Android workload bundles its own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17), so the build system actually uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property rather than relying on the system JAVA_HOME. With .NET 9 and the Android 35 SDK, there's likely a requirement for JDK 21, which could create version conflicts if the bundled JDK doesn't match what the Android build tools expect. .NET MAUI includes its own bundled JDK by default, so even if `JAVA_HOME` is set correctly, the build might ignore it entirely and use Microsoft's OpenJDK distribution instead, which could cause version mismatches. Since the user confirmed `java -version` works fine, the Java installation itself isn't the problem—I need to dig deeper into what's actually failing in the build. me reconsider. The most common .NET MAUI Android + Java error scenarios:\n\n1. **\"Could not determine java version\"** or similar - version parsing issue\n2. **\"Unsupported class file major version\"** - JDK too new\n3. **\"JavaSdkDirectory\" not found** \n4. **Android SDK build-tools version incompatibility with the JDK**\n\nActually, I think I know what the real issue likely is. In recent .NET (8+), the Android workload ships with a bundled JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17). The build system looks for Java in this order:\n1. `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property\n2. The bundled JDK from the Android workload\n3. `JAVA_HOME`\n4. `PATH`\n\nIf the bundled JDK is present, `JAVA_HOME` might be ignored, and if it's not present, there could be path resolution issues. Without the exact error message, I'm thinking the most likely culprit in April 2026 is that .NET 9 or later requires JDK 21 for Android builds, but the user only has JDK 17 installed, which no longer meets the minimum requirements for the newer Android build tools and API levels. I know for sure:\n\n- .NET 8 Android: requires JDK 17 (bundles Microsoft OpenJDK 17)\n- .NET 9 Android: The shift toward JDK 21 started. Android Gradle Plugin 8.2+ works with JDK 17 but AGP 8.4+ and Android SDK build-tools 35+ may need JDK 21.\n\nGiven it's April 2026, the user is likely on .NET 9 or .NET 10, both of which would require JDK 21.\n\nThe fix would be: Install JDK 21 (e.g., `brew install --cask temurin@21`) and update JAVA_HOME.\n\nThe most likely culprit here is that JDK 17 is too old for the current .NET MAUI Android build tools—by April 2026, .NET 9 and likely .NET 10 would need JDK 21. The error messages would probably mention something about Java version incompatibility or unsupported class file versions.","outputTokens":2013,"requestId":"9BD2:11AB75:61FC429:6D27063:69EC0E53"},"id":"b114d1fb-637d-47fa-8250-a864292ae6ad","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:44:40.396Z","parentId":"a6de8857-89c5-40f9-820c-dbe0bdf1acd7"}
